{{日本の寺院 |名称 = {{ill|Koyama-ji|ja|甲山寺}} |画像 = Kōyama-ji, Main Hall 001.jpg |画像サイズ = 250 |画像説明 = Main Hall |所在地 = {{ill|Kagawa Prefecture|ja|香川県}}{{ill|Zentsūji City|ja|善通寺市}} 弘田町1765-1 |位置 = {{Coord|34|13|59.5|N|133|45|56.75|E|type:landmark_region:JP-37|display=inline,title}} |山号 = {{ill|Iōzan|ja|医王山}} |院号 = {{ill|Taho-in|ja|多宝院}} |宗旨 = |宗派 = {{ill|Shingon Shentsū-ji Sect|ja|真言宗善通寺派}} |寺格 = |本尊 = {{ill|Yakushi Nyorai|ja|薬師如来}} |創建年 = (伝) {{ill|Kōnin|ja|弘仁}}12年 ({{ill|821|ja|821年}}) |開山 = |開基 = (伝) {{ill|Kūkai|ja|空海}} ({{ill|Kōbō Daishi|ja|弘法大師}}) |中興年 = |中興 = |正式名 = {{ill|Iōzan Taho-in Koyama-ji|ja|医王山 多宝院 甲山寺}} |別称 = |札所等 = {{ill|Shikoku 88 Temples|ja|四国八十八箇所}} No.74 |文化財 = |公式HP = https://koyamaji.or.jp/ |公式HP名 = [Kagawa] Iōzan Taho-in Koyama-ji |地図2 = {{Switcher | {{Location map+|Japan Kagawa|width=230|caption= |float=center|places= {{Location map~|Japan Kagawa|lat_deg=34|lat_min=13|lat_sec=59.5|lon_deg=133|lon_min=45|lon_sec=56.75|mark=Indian_Swastika.svg|marksize=12|position=left|label={{ill|Koyama-ji|ja|甲山寺}}|label_size=100|caption=}} {{Location map~|Japan Kagawa|lat_deg=34|lat_min=21|lat_sec=2.46|lon_deg=134|lon_min=2|lon_sec=48.98|mark=blue pog.svg|position=top|label={{ill|Takamatsu Station (Kagawa)|ja|高松駅}}|label_size=95}} {{Location map~|Japan Kagawa|lat_deg=34|lat_min=12|lat_sec=51|lon_deg=134|lon_min=0|lon_sec=56|mark=BSicon FLUGg.svg|marksize=10|position=bottom|label={{ill|Takamatsu Airport|ja|高松空港}}|label_size=95}}}} | Position in Kagawa Prefecture | {{maplink2|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=point|zoom=14|frame-align=center|frame-width=230}} | Position in Zentsūji City }} }}
'''Koyama-ji''' (甲山寺, こうやまじ) is a temple of the {{ill|Shingon Shentsū-ji Sect|ja|真言宗善通寺派}} located in {{ill|Kagawa Prefecture|ja|香川県}}, {{ill|Zentsūji City|ja|善通寺市}}. It is also known by its mountain name, {{ill|Iōzan|ja|医王山}}, and by its temple name, {{ill|Taho-in|ja|多宝院}}. The principal image is {{ill|Yakushi Nyorai|ja|薬師如来}}, and it is the 74th temple on the {{ill|Shikoku 88 Temples|ja|四国八十八箇所}} pilgrimage. The temple is situated at the foot of {{ill|Koyama (Kagawa)|ja|甲山}} (also called Kabutoyama).
* The mantra of the principal image is: "on korokoro sendarimātōgi sowaka" (おん ころころ せんだりまとうぎ そわか). * The temple hymn (ご詠歌) is: "In battles where the Twelve Deities (十二神) are my allies, may my heart be like Koyama" (十二神味方に持てる戦には おのれとこころ甲やまかな). * The Nōkyō seal includes the temple’s principal image, the guardian deity {{ill|Tamonten|ja|多聞天堂毘沙門天}}, and a rabbit seal (worth 200 yen).
== Overview == {{File:Kouyamaji20210309 1.jpg|170px|left|thumb|Koyama-ji}} According to legend, during his prime, {{ill|Kūkai|ja|空海}} once explored this area—where he had played as a child—and encountered an old man who prophesied that a temple should be built here. Believing the old man to be an incarnation of {{ill|Bishamonten|ja|毘沙門天}} who dwelled in a local cave, Kūkai enshrined Bishamonten in that cave. Later, upon receiving an imperial edict from Emperor {{ill|Saga|ja|嵯峨天皇}} to rebuild {{ill|Mannō-ike|ja|満濃池}}, Kūkai inscribed an image of {{ill|Yakushi Nyorai|ja|薬師如来}} and conducted rituals that drew tens of thousands of people, leading to the successful completion of the temple's construction. In the 12th year of the {{ill|Kōnin era|ja|弘仁}} (821), the imperial court awarded 20,000 sen in recognition of his achievements, a portion of which was used to construct the temple, marking its founding.
During the battles of the {{ill|Tenshō era|ja|天正}} period, only the principal image and a few temple treasures survived. The "Shikoku Henrei Reishōki" (published in 1689) records that "even though it was once a grand temple, it had fallen into ruin—as is the fate of many things." However, the main hall was rebuilt in the 20th year of the {{ill|Kyōhō era|ja|享保}} (1730), and the Daisidō (Great Master Hall) was rebuilt in the 2nd year of the {{ill|Kanpō era|ja|寛保}} (1742). An illustration in the "Shikoku Henrei Meisho Zukai" (published in 1800) shows a form close to the present one.
On {{ill|Koyama (Kagawa)|ja|甲山}} (elevation 87.2 m), it is said that during the Muromachi period an outpost of {{ill|Amagiri Castle|ja|天霧城}} once stood, evidenced by a stone stage on the summit and the presence of a commemorative stone dedicated to Emperor {{ill|Jimmu|ja|神武天皇}} and Emperor {{ill|Kōmyō|ja|孝明天皇}}. In addition, along the mountain path from the temple to the summit, stone Buddhas—dating from the late Edo period and part of the {{ill|Nishi-koku 33 Kannon Pilgrimage|ja|西国三十三所}}—are arrayed.<ref>According to local signage.</ref>
== Temple Complex == {{File:Kouyamaji kyuusannmonn1.jpg|100px|thumb|Old Main Gate}} {{File:Kouyamaji bisyamongutu1.jpg|100px|thumb|Old Bishamonten Cave}} * **Main Gate:** Fell into disrepair in 2008. * **Middle Gate:** Rebuilt in 1769 (the 6th year of the {{ill|Meiwa era|ja|明和}}) as the middle gate. * **Main Hall:** Completed in 1735 (the 20th year of the {{ill|Kyōhō era|ja|享保}}). Visitors are required to remove their footwear to view the principal image. The principal image is a seated statue of {{ill|Yakushi Nyorai|ja|薬師如来}} (a monolithic carving from Hiwamatsu with carved eyes); the attendant Buddhas include a standing statue of {{ill|Nikkō Gekkō Bosatsu|ja|日光月光菩薩}}, a standing statue of {{ill|Bishamonten|ja|毘沙門天}} on the right flank, and a seated statue of {{ill|Amida Nyorai|ja|阿弥陀如来}} on the left. * **Daisidō (Great Master Hall):** Completed in 1742 (the 2nd year of the {{ill|Kanpō era|ja|寛保}}). A statue of the Great Master in black robes was unveiled in 2014 and 2020. * **Guest Hall:** Features fusuma painted with the Heart Sutra by calligrapher Kohei Okamoto. * **Goma Hall:** Completed in 1782 (the 2nd year of the {{ill|Tenmei era|ja|天明}}). Houses a seated statue of {{ill|Fudō Myōō|ja|不動明王}} and two child attendants. * **Tsuya Jizō:** Located to the right in front of the Daisidō; according to tradition, carrying its apron is said to bring about the birth of a child. * **Awashima Daimyōjin Shrine (Hokora)** * **Bell Tower:** Completed in 1752 (the 2nd year of the {{ill|Hōreki era|ja|宝暦}}). * **16 Rabbits:** Derived from depictions of rabbits on the accessory of the attendant Buddha {{ill|Gekkō Bosatsu|ja|月光菩薩}} beside the principal image, rabbits are represented on the interior of the Main and Middle Gates, as well as on the roof of the tea house and in front of the chozubasho.<ref>{{Cite news |和書 |title=Welcome to Rabbit Temple – “16 Rabbits” present on the precincts, also used as talismans at Zentsūji/Koyama-ji |newspaper=Shikoku Shimbun |date=2020-04-03 |url=https://www.shikoku-np.co.jp/bl/digital_news/article.aspx?id=K2020040300000001300 |accessdate=2023-07-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405172931/http://www.shikoku-np.co.jp/bl/digital_news/article.aspx?id=K2020040300000001300 |archivedate=2020-04-05 }}</ref> * Proceeding through the Main Gate and past the hand-washing basin to the right, turning left to pass through the Middle Gate leads to a Nōkyō (scripture hall) on the right. A short flight of stone steps then leads to the Main Hall; to its right lies the Goma Hall, and a few steps up on the left is the Daisidō. Beyond that is the Bell Tower, and further on is the entrance to the Bishamonten Cave, within which a stone statue of Bishamonten is enshrined. * **Lodging (Shukubō):** None. * **Parking:** A free large parking lot is available in front of the Main Gate. * **Suijin Shrine (Hokora):** Enshrined at the highest point of the precincts. * **Mini Nishi-koku 33 Kannon Pilgrimage:** Markers along the walking path from the precincts to the summit.
== Cultural Properties == ; National Historic Site * The pilgrimage route of the {{ill|Sanuki Pilgrimage|ja|遍路道}} within the precincts of Koyama-ji – This route originally wound eastward around the northern part of Koyama, reached the old Main Gate, then crossed a stone bridge (now removed) over the Hirota River in front of Zentsūji, continuing south. It was recommended in a report on December 20, Reiwa 6.<ref>https://www.pref.kagawa.lg.jp/documents/51893/kouyamazi_shitei.pdf</ref>
== Transportation == ; **Rail** * {{ill|Shikoku Railway Company (JR Shikoku)|ja|四国旅客鉄道}}, {{ill|Tosan Line|ja|土讃線}} – {{ill|Zentsūji Station|ja|善通寺駅}} (3.6 km) ; **Road** * Public road: {{ill|Kagawa Prefectural Road 48: Zentsūji Tarima Line|ja|香川県道48号善通寺詫間線}} – Zentsūji Ballpark (0.3 km) * Expressway: {{ill|Takamatsu Expressway|ja|高松自動車道}}, {{ill|Zentsūji Interchange|ja|善通寺インターチェンジ}} (4.5 km)
